this is one of my favorites along with the mariette hartley and robert lansing " sandy " and the agnes moorhead - and - the - tiny - spacemen episodes .
it is an important take , from mid-1961 , on the long cold war that the u.s. was then embroiled in .
the beaten - down city - scene , the near - starving characters ' sparse dialog , their threadbare uniforms , and the minimal action " says " it all : the absurdity of an on - going conflict that threatens to destroy human life , modern civilization , and all that is sweet and redeeming about it .
it is a " fable " because it was made in a time in which , had events turned out differently , such as the second berlin crisis ( spring 1961 ) and the subsequent cuban missile crisis ( oct. 1962 ) , it would have actually been a reasonable representation of one of the u.s. 's major cities , ruined and replete with a few miserable survivors .
i also see it as a " fable " because it is not only a cautionary tale , but because it is the most redemptive of all our popular myths : it is a love story , set in an impossible situation , and involving two highly mismatched lovers .
